## Attribution

This course was developed in dialogue with two openly published bodies of work. Neither is
reproduced here; both shaped how the course is built, and both deserve credit.

### Applied AI Systems and Governance (PPG2012H)

**Jaxson Khan**, University of Toronto, Munk School of Global Affairs & Public Policy —
https://github.com/jaxson/ai-policy-course

The course architecture and pedagogy are modelled on this course: the participatory seminar
format, the escalating briefing-note structure, the policy-memo-or-AI-agent capstone with student
choice of track, and the practice of pairing conceptual sessions with hands-on AI work. The
original is shared by its author for educational use with attribution.

### Teaching Public Service in the Digital Age

https://www.teachingpublicservice.digital

TPSDA provided the digital-era government backbone: its Digital Era Competencies, its unit
structure, and much of the reading spine on data, administrative burden, algorithmic harm, and
barriers to change. TPSDA materials are published openly to help faculty add digital-era skills to
MPP and MPA teaching. Honey Dacanay is a Founding Contributor and Research Lead to TPSDA.

### If you adapt this course

Please credit all three:

- this course — Honey Dacanay, McMaster University School of Public Policy
- Jaxson Khan, *Applied AI Systems and Governance*, University of Toronto Munk School
- Teaching Public Service in the Digital Age (teachingpublicservice.digital)

